			<ns0:name>pa...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/101628056640429344673/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Currently the R-DFA validator recognizes more instructions than the production validator (AVX, XOP, etc.)

It is less of a problem with the validator itself, since we can mask off the corresponding CPUFeatures in the validator (I think we are _not_ doing that).

More of a problem is ability to enumerate instructions from the set allowed by the R-DFA validator. Or subsets of those. The 3 operand instructions take most of the time/space, make the interesting comparisons a lot less efficient.

These families need to be put off to separate .def files: AVX, XOP, FMA*, BMI1, TBM. Ideally the production DFA should be generated without those, but that would be a separate issue.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2013-04-09T19:54:26.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-07-05T14:39:08.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>WontFix</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
